No's. 9 to 19 Fifth Avenue, at, adjoining and north of the N. E. corner of East 8th treet, showing prominently the cafe of the Hotel Brevoort. The Hotel is composed of three structures and which bear No's. 9 to 17 inclusive. Adjoining same is a four story basement dwelling with white window trim. This is No. 19 . At the left margin appears a portion of the Samuel Clemens(kark Twain) house, located at the S. E. corner of East 9th Street. 13 East 8th Street (formerly 55 Clinton Place), the house with the large vine, has been for some years the home of Richard Watson Gilder, author and Editor-in-Chief (since 1881) of The  tur  SSS28N2 NAEEE105. who will continue to reside here till his deatn, un 1909. EiEHthiStreet, west of Broadway, used to be called Clinton Place, the houses being numbered west from Broadway. The name and numbering was changed in 1899. As may be seen in this picture, the street has already lost its residential character. Nearly thirty years later this scene will not have changed greatly. Mr. Giloer's house will have been remodelled like No. V; the parlor store will be occupied by Fred Leighton's Indian Trading Post, and the basement
by a gown shop and an interior decorator.
April 11, 1906.
Brown Brothers.
